<article>
    <h1>HOME AP&#xAD;PLI&#xAD;ANCES GET SMART</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201121/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-21"><time>2020-11-21</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | DESIGN</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The Elec­trolux Life App (left) cre­ates fu­tur­is­tic sce­nar­ios where house­hold ap­pli­ances are im­bued with ar­ti­fi­cial in­tel­li­gence (AI).</p>
    <p>It is a col­lab­o­ra­tion be­tween lead­ing global ap­pli­ance com­pany Elec­trolux and IBM sub­sidiary The Weather Com­pany, a global ex­pert on weather and cli­mate data.</p>
    <p>An Elec­trolux home ap­pli­ance is now able to scan the weather fore­cast and give its user rec­om­men­da­tions – like when to start the dryer be­cause it is about to rain or when to switch off the air pu­ri­fier be­cause the air qual­ity for that day is good.</p>
    <p>Smart ap­pli­ances can be con­nected via a few clicks to the app, pow­ered by IBM’s next-gen­er­a­tion AI-en­abled weather fore­cast­ing tech­nol­ogy.</p>
    <p>Com­pil­ing hy­per-lo­calised data such as air qual­ity, pollen lev­els and hu­mid­ity data from IBM’s weather data API, the app will pro­vide users with the best data to make the most in­formed de­ci­sion about their en­ergy con­sump­tion and the op­ti­mal use of their ap­pli­ances.</p>
    <p>Info: www.elec­trolux.com.sg/ sup­port/elec­trolux-life-app</p>

